# Cowrie Honeypot Lab (Cybersecurity Project)

This project demonstrates the deployment of a Cowrie SSH honeypot,
network reconnaissance, simulated attacks, traffic capture, and log analysis
in a controlled lab environment.


# Lab Environment
- Ubuntu / Debian (Honeypot VM)
- Kali Linux (Attacker VM)
- Cowrie SSH Honeypot
- Nmap, Hydra, Wireshark, tcpdump

# Used Ubuntu Server 22.04 LTS (Jammy Jellyfish) on VirtualBox.
https://releases.ubuntu.com/22.04/ubuntu-22.04.4-live-server-amd64.iso
#If you’re getting errors, make sure:
* You’re using Ubuntu 20.04 or 22.04 LTS
* Python3 and virtualenv are installed
* You’re not running Cowrie as root, Purpose:
#Creates a non-root user to safely run the honeypot.
#Create a Dedicated Honeypot User

##Part 1: Environment Setup (Ubuntu/Debian)
#Install dependencies
$ sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
$ sudo apt install git python3-virtualenv libssl-dev libffi-dev build-essential python3-dev -y

#Install Cowrie
$ git clone https://github.com/cowrie/cowrie
$ cd cowrie
$ virtualenv cowrie-env
$ source cowrie-env/bin/activate
$ pip install --upgrade pip
$ pip install -r requirements.txt
$ pip install -e .
$ Start Cowrie
$ cowrie init
$ cowrie start
$ cowrie status

##Part 2: Network Reconnaissance (Kali Linux)
#Identify Honeypot IP
$ ip addr show

#Host Discovery
$ nmap -sn <HONEYPOT_IP>

#Port Scanning & Enumeration
$ nmap -sV -p- <HONEYPOT_IP>
$ nmap --script vuln <HONEYPOT_IP>

##Part 3: Simulated Attacks
#SSH Login Attempts
$ ssh root@<HONEYPOT_IP> -p 2222

#Brute Force Attack (Hydra)
$ hydra -l root -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt ssh://<HONEYPOT_IP>:2222
#Custom Password List
$ echo -e "password\nroot\n123456\nadmin" > passwords.txt
$ hydra -l root -P passwords.txt ssh://<HONEYPOT_IP>:2222

#Banner Grabbing
$ nc <HONEYPOT_IP> 2222
$ telnet <HONEYPOT_IP> 2222

#Multiple Connection Attempts
$ for i in {1..10}; do ssh root@<HONEYPOT_IP> -p 2222; done

##Part 4: Traffic Capture & Analysis
#Capture Traffic
$ sudo tcpdump -i eth0 host <HONEYPOT_IP> -w attack_capture.pcap
$ sudo tcpdump -i eth0 port 2222 -w honeypot_traffic.pcap

#Analyze Traffic
$ tcpdump -r attack_capture.pcap
$ wireshark attack_capture.pcap

##Part 5: Log Analysis
#View Logs
$ cat var/log/cowrie/cowrie.log
$ cat var/log/cowrie/cowrie.json

#Install jq
$ sudo apt install jq

#Analyze Events
$ grep "authentication" var/log/cowrie/cowrie.json | jq .
$ grep "login" var/log/cowrie/cowrie.json | jq .
$ grep "cowrie.login.failed" var/log/cowrie/cowrie.json | jq .
$ grep "cowrie.login.success" var/log/cowrie/cowrie.json | jq .

#### Skills Demonstrated
1. Honeypot deployment
2. SSH attack simulation
3. Network reconnaissance
3. Traffic capture
4. Log analysis with jq
